HEADWORD: Perdue
<hw>Per*due"</hw> }</mhw>
<pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*d⟦umac⟧" <it>or</it> p⟦etil⟧r"d⟦usl⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>perdu</ets>, f. <ets>perdue</ets>, lost, p. p. of
<ets>perdre</ets> to lose, L. <ets>perdere</ets>. See
<er>Perdition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lost to view; in concealment
or ambush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He should lie <qex>perdue</qex> who is to walk the round.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Accustomed to, or employed in, desperate
enterprises; hence, reckless; hopeless.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>perdue</xex>
captain.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perduellion</ent>⟦br⟧
